stylometry: The overall objective of fixed cost models is to see whether or not we incur fixed costs. If a certain activity is not implemented, then we do not incur fixed costs for this activity. Other than trying to figure out which fixed costs to incur, in a fixed cost model, we are also trying to minimize the total cost. This is important because you do not want to incur fixed costs for activities that are not even being implemented. Set covering models are when you are trying to minimize the number of members in set 2 that are needed to cover the members in set 1. This is important because you want to make sure that all members are covered. An example of a fixed cost model is selling tshirts, shorts, skirts, and jackets. If you are in the business to sell these items, but want to minimize total costs, you may only end up producing shirts and jackets. Costs incurred would be the variable costs to make the shirts and jackets (and all labor, etc.), as well as the fixed costs of the shirts and jackets. Since shorts and skirts are not being produced, the fixed costs of these items will not be incurred.
